{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_kingsombra_ver01/data/sn87065031/00415662117/1921010901/0021.xml":{"full_text":"S. 4\n1-\nJ.\nv.\nl.v-\nJS\nView of the Salvation Army's Christmas Party at Army Headquarters.\nA PEEP INTO THE FUTURE\n(Continued from Fai?e One.)\"'\nhas faith in the pood old UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, will do well to\npurchase the January 8th issue of The Literary Digest and read Pages 7-8-9,\nan article entitled, WHEN WILL HOOD TIMES RETURN 7\nv In thin article the leaders of the country, both in finance and industry,\npoint out that the country will enter a period of SOUND prosperity early\nin 1921.\n\"Lowndes County,' Mississippi, is a part of the U. S. A.'. 'It is rich in\nnatural resources. Its people are 100 per cent Americans and producers of\nwealth. By hard work and co-operation the people of Lowndes County will\npet their shnre of tjie coming prosperity.\n\"As The. Literary Biprst says, As day follows night, and flood-tide\nfollows 'ibb, $o jlnfVitcfy nwt h existing 'business' depression sometime\ncome to an end and the irJIooding tides of prosperity begin to rise,'\nMR. IRA L GAslON, Cashier of the First State Hank. v'\nResponding to your request for an expression of opinion on the outlook\nand conditions generally, I submit the following which was clipped from The\nLiterary Digest and headed When Will Good Times Return\nAs day follows niht, and flood-tide follows ebb, rot inevitablymust the\nexisting business depression some time, come to an end and the inflooding\ntides of prosperity beirm to rise. At least, so all our historians, economists,\nbankers, and financial authorities agree. (But what the anxious business man\nasks just now is, When will the tide turn, when will. the dawn break, when\nwill the buvef cease from striking, and the wheels of industry again begin\nto revolve?\" To these questions, after a careful search of the daily and finan\ncial press, we are at least able to give an answer from men who should know\nwhereof they speak. The Federal Reserve monthly bulletin, The Annalist,\nthe current report of the Harvard Committee on economic research, the review\nof the National City Bank,\" as it is noted in The Nation, all agree in a gen\neral expectation that the industrial depression accompanying the process of\ndeflation will last into the spring, but that a revival is due to begin by March\nor April.\" Other, authorities who venture predictions agree in a general way\nthat while the depression is likely to he worse before it is better, there ai\nalready signs of improvement, and a definite recovery is to be expected, some\nsayj by' the em! of tlW present month; -Others' put the date 'any whertr from\none to six months in tbo future. Mr. A. W. Douglas, who beads the commit\ntee on statistics of the United States Chamber of Commerce, in a report based\non investigation throughout the country, makes the encouraging declaration\nthat we are near the bottom of the depression, or will be in the next thirty\ndays.\" In a forecast prepared for. Forbes, the. banking and brokerage firm\nof Homblower Weeks asserts its belief that the current industrial de\npression will end in February.\" Mr. E. 3. Cattell, Philadelphia city statist\ntician, predicted at a recent luncheon in New York that the end of the busi\nness depression will come in February or March; that from then on for a\nperiod of two or three months business would improve slowly, and by the first\nof October should be going ahead at fall speed. Mr. Frank F. Porter, chair\nman of the Firwe ComiuiHce of the National Industrial Council, last month\npredicted better business cot,.1k!ons within ninety days. The. Harvard eco\nnomic .committee holdw to iLs ..recast that \"tho recession of business now in\nprogress will terminate by A il, 11)21.\" Mr. John Moody, the authority oh\nsecurities, is convinced that a business revival will occur during 1921, and\nespecially after the end of the first quarter; for such a revival is definitely\nforeshadowed by the present abundance of material and labor, and by the\nabundance of cupital which we will probably soon see.\" The December letter\nof the 'Alexander Hamilton Institute contains a careful survey of the pros\npects of business reviyal. In the first place, it is asserted that the banking\ni risis was really passed in November, a statement supported in part by the\ndrop in the interest-rates on call loans and time loans. The prediction that\nmoney-rates will be much easier in 1921 is based by the certainty that both\nthe farmer and retailer will have to pay off loans in large amounts during\nthe coming months and that loan requirements in 1921 will be conspicuously\nsmaller.\" There is thought likely to be little large-scale expansion by cor\nporations before 1922, because of interest charges. By the summer of\nt'J21 conditions may favor a moderate dctn'n of new construction work and\nretail buying, but during the first half of 1921 we shall have to pass through\nthe period of liquidation which normally conies between prosperity and the\npoint of complete re-adjustment.\" Thellow prices which come with' depres\nsion bear in themMves the conditions necessary for revival. Firnt, \"they\nproduce easier money conditions and stimulate the issue of bonds.\" Secondly,,\n\"low prices in themselves stimulate larger purchases. There are many thou\nsands of people waiting to buy furniture, clothing, and luxuries when prices\nappear to be at the end of their decline.\"\nINFORMATION TO\nRIVER SHIPPERS\nNotice is sent out from the Missis\nsippi-Warrior river service head\nquarters in New Orleans calling at\ntention to the next trip dates of the\ngovernment self-propelled barges.\nThe barge Birmingham departs on\nthe up-river j trip on January, 11 and\nthe Tuscaloosa leaves the following\nday.\nOne large Columbus shipper hag\nalready issued' shipping instructions\nto route his '-heary'. shipments of\nstaples over the Warrior, taking .ad\nvantage thereby of the 20 per cent\ndifferential in freight .rates. f i t,\nFollowing is some \"valuable informa-\ntin relative to the river traffic:\nFreight for these sailings will be\nreceived at our Poydras Street Wharf\nat the foot of canal street New Or\nleans, until 5. p. m., January 10 and\nJanuary 11th respectively.\nShipments from New Orleans and\nMobile, to points in the states of\nAlabama, Georgia, Mississippi and\nTennessee, are earnestly solicited.\nPublished freight rates offering\ndifferentials of \"Jwenty per cent, un\nder the All-rail rates are In effect,\nand through bills of lading are issued\nby the Barge Linecovering water\nand ail shipments;'; iT;\nV\nMade on or before Jan. 10th\nbear interest as of Jan. 1st\nWe\nPay\nWo\nY\nCompounded\nSemi-annually\nt i\nV .if; I tl\nv.\n..if'; i\nh it\nColumbus, niGGissippi\n3k\nDay\nWe Gin Every\nWe have an electrically-driven gin plant, and are in a\nposition to gin your cotton on ANY DAY'. For QUICK and\nEFFICIENT service, wc solicit your patronage.\nIndependent Oil Fertilizer Works\nFntiSffMEN' ELECT OFFICERS.\nThe Freshmari class, the largest rn\nthe' Mississippi: State' College for Wo\nmen, hold its election of officers for\nthe Bession immediately after the re\nturn of the students from the holidays\nthe past wek.\nThe election resulted as follows:\nPresident, Miss Lucille McRaven,\nYazoo City; Vice-President, MisB\nHazel Peery, Eupora; Secretary and\nTreasurer, Miss Elizabeth Smith, Hat\ntiesburg; Business Manager, Miss\nDabney Ledyard.\nA WORD TO MEN\nAll men who have not yet bought a\nsuit and overcoat, or who will heed a\nsuit during the next six months, will\ndo well to read the advertisement in\nthis paper of Simon Loeb Bro,\nThis is an unusual opportunity, as\nyou will find if you will call at the\nstore and compare prices and values.\nONLY TWO CONCLUSIONS\nIf you do not purchase merchandise\nat Beard's sale now, there are only\ntwo conclusions you either don't\nneed it or you have no money. The\nprices have struck rock bottom.